# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: web-bluetooth
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] The **`Bluetooth`** interface of the Web Bluetooth API provides methods to query Bluetooth availability and request access to devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to a boolean value indicating whether the user agent can support Bluetooth.
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] Some user agents let the user configure an option that specifies what value is returned by this method.
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to an array of `BluetoothDevice`s this origin is allowed to access.
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] Permission is obtained via previous calls to `Bluetooth.requestDevice()`.
[src:web-bluetooth/api-bluetooth] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `BluetoothDevice` object matching the specified options.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] BLE and Classic Bluetooth use different sets of radio frequencies, and although BLE is independent of classic Bluetooth and has no direct compatibility, Bluetooth Basic Rate/Enhanced Data Rate (BR/EDR) and BLE can coexist.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The original specification was developed by Nokia in 2006 under the name Wibree, which was integrated into Bluetooth 4.0 in December 2009 as Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Mobile operating systems including iOS, Android, Windows Phone and BlackBerry, as well as the desktop computer operating systems macOS, Linux, Windows 8, Windows 10 and Windows 11, natively support Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy is distinct from the previous (often called "classic") Bluetooth Basic Rate/Enhanced Data Rate (BR/EDR) protocol, but the two protocols can both be supported by one device: the Bluetooth 4.0 specification permits devices to implement either or both of the LE and BR/EDR systems.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy uses the same 2.4 GHz radio frequencies as classic Bluetooth, which allows dual-mode devices to share a single radio antenna, but uses a simpler modulation system.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In 2011, the Bluetooth SIG announced the Bluetooth Smart logo so as to clarify compatibility between the new low-energy devices and other Bluetooth devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] With the May 2016 Bluetooth SIG branding information, the Bluetooth SIG began phasing out the Bluetooth Smart and Bluetooth Smart Ready logos and word marks and reverted to using the Bluetooth logo and word mark in a new blue color.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth SIG identifies a number of markets for low-energy technology, particularly in the smart home, health, sport, and fitness sectors.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In 2001, researchers at Nokia determined various scenarios that contemporary wireless technologies did not address.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The company began developing a wireless technology adapted from the Bluetooth standard which would provide lower power usage and cost while minimizing its differences from Bluetooth technology.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The results were published in 2004 using the name Bluetooth Low End Extension.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] After further development with partners, in particular Logitech and within the European project MIMOSA, and actively promoted and supported by STMicroelectronics since its early stage, the technology was released to the public in October 2006 with the brand name Wibree.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] After negotiations with Bluetooth SIG members, an agreement was reached in June 2007 to include Wibree in a future Bluetooth specification as a Bluetooth ultra-low-power technology.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The technology was marketed as Bluetooth Smart and integration into version 4.0 of the Core Specification was completed in early 2010.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The first smartphone to implement the 4.0 specification was the iPhone 4S, released in October 2011.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A number of other manufacturers released Bluetooth Low Energy Ready devices in 2012.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth SIG officially unveiled Bluetooth 5 on 16 June 2016 during a media event in London.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] One change on the marketing side was that the point number was dropped, so it is now just called Bluetooth 5 (and not Bluetooth 5.0 or 5.0 LE like for Bluetooth 4.0).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This decision was made to "simplify marketing, and communicate user benefits more effectively".
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] An "advertising packet" in Bluetooth parlance is the information that is exchanged between two devices *before* pairing, i.e. when they are not connected.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] For example, advertising packets allow a device to display to the user the name of another Bluetooth device before pairing with it.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth 5 increased the data length of this advertising packet.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The length of this packet in Bluetooth 4.x was 31 bytes (for broadcast topology).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth SIG officially released Mesh Profile and Mesh Model specifications on 18 July 2017.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Mesh specification enables using Bluetooth Low Energy for many-to-many device communications for home automation, sensor networks, and other applications, where sensors, robots, smartphones, and other equipment need to be coordinated.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Borrowing from the original Bluetooth specification, the Bluetooth SIG defines several profiles – specifications for how a device works in a particular application – for low-energy devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Manufacturers are expected to implement the appropriate specifications for their device in order to ensure compatibility.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A device may contain implementations of multiple profiles.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The majority of current Low Energy application profiles are based on the Generic Attribute Profile (GATT), a general specification for sending and receiving short pieces of data, known as attributes, over a low-energy link.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The Bluetooth mesh profile is an exception to this rule, being based on the General Access Profile (GAP).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth mesh profiles use Bluetooth Low Energy to communicate with other Bluetooth Low Energy devices in the network.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Each device can pass the information forward to other Bluetooth Low Energy devices, creating a "mesh" effect – for example, switching off an entire building of lights from a single smartphone.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] There are many profiles for Bluetooth Low Energy devices in healthcare applications.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] "Electronic leash" applications are well-suited to the long battery life possible for "always-on" devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Manufacturers of iBeacon devices implement the appropriate specifications for their device to make use of proximity-sensing capabilities supported by Apple's iOS devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] An example of proximity sensing usage is WebAuthn Hybrid Transport with cloud-assisted Bluetooth Low Energy (caBLE), allowing roaming authenticators such as smartphones to authenticate with WebAuthn credential (known as passkey).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy is used as a proximity check between roaming authenticators and clients (such as personal computers).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Announced in January 2020, LE Audio is built on top of Bluetooth 5.2 / 5.3.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] It allows the Bluetooth LE protocol to carry audio, with lower battery consumption compared to regular Bluetooth Audio; features like one set of headphones connecting to multiple audio sources or multiple headphones connecting to one source (known as Auracast); and support for hearing aids.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The standard has a lower minimum latency claim of 20–30 ms vs.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Specifications on the implementation of Basic Audio Profile and Coordinated Set Identification was released in 2021, and the Common Audio Profile and Service in March 2022.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] On 12 July 2022, the Bluetooth SIG announced the completion of Bluetooth LE Audio.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Auracast implements public audio broadcasting services, allowing multiple receivers to connect to a single audio transmitter without going through Bluetooth device pairing first.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] It is a trademark owned by the Bluetooth SIG.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth LE–enabled smartphones function as an assistant to control Auracast receivers like headphones and earbuds.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Broadcast Audio URI, marketed as "Scan to Listen", provides information required to connect to the specific audio stream, encoded with a QR code or transmitted using NFC.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Developed by the MIDI Manufacturers Association (MMA) Working Group (now The MIDI Association), there is a formalized Bluetooth LE MIDI (BLE-MIDI) specification, a wireless protocol designed to transmit MIDI data over Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] It focuses on power-efficient wireless MIDI communication for devices such as MIDI controllers, keyboards, pedals, etc., that don't continuously stream data – and without significant latency.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Operating systems that support it include Windows 10 Version 1607, macOS and Android.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In December 2020, the Bluetooth SIG released a draft specification for a wearable exposure-notification service.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This service allows exposure-notification services on wearable devices to communicate with, and be controlled by, client devices such as smartphones.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Starting in late 2009, Bluetooth Low Energy integrated circuits were announced by a number of manufacturers.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] These ICs commonly use software radio, so updates to the specification can be accommodated through a firmware upgrade.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Current mobile devices are commonly released with hardware and software support for both classic Bluetooth and Bluetooth Low Energy.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy technology operates in the same spectrum range (the 2.400–2.4835 GHz ISM band) as classic Bluetooth technology, but uses a different set of channels.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Instead of the classic Bluetooth 79 1-MHz channels, Bluetooth Low Energy has 40 2-MHz channels.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Within a channel, data is transmitted using Gaussian frequency shift modulation, similar to classic Bluetooth's Basic Rate scheme.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The bit rate is 1 Mbit/s (with an option of 2 Mbit/s in Bluetooth 5), and the maximum transmit power is 10 mW (100 mW in Bluetooth 5).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Further details are given in Volume 6 Part A (Physical Layer Specification) of the Bluetooth Core Specification V4.0.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy uses frequency hopping to counteract narrowband interference problems.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Classic Bluetooth also uses frequency hopping but the details are different; as a result, while both FCC and ETSI classify Bluetooth technology as an FHSS scheme, Bluetooth Low Energy is classified as a system using digital modulation techniques or a direct-sequence spread spectrum.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] More technical details may be obtained from official specification as published by the Bluetooth SIG.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Note that power consumption is not part of the Bluetooth specification.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] BLE devices are detected through a procedure based on broadcasting advertising packets.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This is done using 3 separate channels (frequencies), in order to reduce interference.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The advertising device sends a packet on at least one of these three channels, with a repetition period called the advertising interval.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] For reducing the chance of multiple consecutive collisions, a random delay of up to 10 milliseconds is added to each advertising interval.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The scanner listens to the channel for a duration called the scan window, which is periodically repeated every scan interval.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The discovery latency is therefore determined by a probabilistic process and depends on the three parameters (viz., the advertising interval, the scan interval and the scan window).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The discovery scheme of BLE adopts a periodic-interval based technique, for which upper bounds on the discovery latency can be inferred for most parametrizations.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy has security instances such as the Encrypted Advertising Data (EAD) feature allowing some or all of the application data payload that is transmitted in advertising packets, to be encrypted.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A standard mechanism for the sharing of key material between a broadcasting device and the observers that are intended to receive this data is also defined, so that the data may be decrypted when received.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] All transmitted Bluetooth LE PDUs include a cyclic redundancy check (CRC) that is recalculated and checked by the receiving device for the possibility of the PDU having been changed in flight.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] All Bluetooth Low Energy devices use the Generic Attribute Profile (GATT).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The application programming interface offered by a Bluetooth Low Energy aware operating system will typically be based around GATT concepts.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A device that initiates GATT commands and requests, and accepts responses, for example, a computer or smartphone.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A device that receives GATT commands and requests, and returns responses, for example, a temperature sensor.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A data value transferred between client and server, for example, the current battery voltage.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A collection of related characteristics, which operate together to perform a particular function.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] service includes characteristics for a temperature measurement value, and a time interval between measurements.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A descriptor provides additional information about a characteristic.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] For instance, a temperature value characteristic may have an indication of its units (e.g.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Celsius), and the maximum and minimum values which the sensor can measure.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Descriptors are optional – each characteristic can have any number of descriptors.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Some service and characteristic values are used for administrative purposes – for instance, the model name and serial number can be read as standard characteristics within the *Generic Access* service.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Services may also include other services as sub-functions; the main functions of the device are so-called *primary* services, and the auxiliary functions they refer to are *secondary* services.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Services, characteristics, and descriptors are collectively referred to as *attributes*, and identified by universally unique identifiers (UUIDs).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Any implementer may pick a random or pseudorandom UUID for proprietary uses, but the Bluetooth SIG have reserved a range of UUIDs (of the form *xxxxxxxx-0000-1000-8000-00805F9B34FB*) for standard attributes.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] For efficiency, these identifiers are represented as 16-bit or 32-bit values in the protocol, rather than the 128 bits required for a full UUID.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] For example, the *Device Information* service has the short code 0x180A, rather than 0000180A-0000-1000-... .
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The full list is kept in the Bluetooth Assigned Numbers document online.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The GATT protocol provides a number of commands for the client to discover information about the server.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Finally, GATT offers *notifications* and *indications*.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The client may request a notification for a particular characteristic from the server.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The server can then send the value to the client whenever it becomes available.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] For instance, a temperature sensor server may notify its client every time it takes a measurement.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This avoids the need for the client to poll the server, which would require the server's radio circuitry to be constantly operational.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] An *indication* is similar to a notification, except that it requires a response from the client, as confirmation that it has received the message.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth Low Energy is designed to enable devices to have very low power consumption.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Several chipmakers including Cambridge Silicon Radio, Dialog Semiconductor, Nordic Semiconductor, STMicroelectronics, Cypress Semiconductor, Silicon Labs and Texas Instruments had introduced Bluetooth Low Energy optimized chipsets by 2014.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Devices with peripheral and central roles have different power requirements.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] A study by beacon software company Aislelabs reported that peripherals such as proximity beacons usually function for 1–2 years powered by a 1,000 mAh coin cell battery.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This is possible because of the power efficiency of Bluetooth Low Energy protocol, which only transmits small packets as compared to Bluetooth Classic which is also suitable for audio and high bandwidth data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In contrast, a continuous scan for the same beacons in central role can consume 1,000 mAh in a few hours.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Android and iOS devices also have very different battery impact depending on type of scans and the number of Bluetooth Low Energy devices in the vicinity.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] With newer chipsets and advances in software, by 2014 both Android and iOS phones had negligible power consumption in real-life Bluetooth Low Energy use.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth 5 has introduced a new transmission mode with a doubled symbol rate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth LE has been traditionally transmitting 1 bit per symbol so that theoretically the data rate doubles as well.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] However, the new mode doubles the bandwidth from about 1 MHz to about 2 MHz which makes for more interferences on the edge regions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The partitioning of the ISM frequency band has not changed being still 40 channels spaced at a distance of 2 MHz.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This is an essential difference over Bluetooth 2 EDR which also doubled the data rate but was doing that by employing a π/4-DQPSK or 8-DPSK phase modulation on a 1 MHz channel while Bluetooth 5 continues to use just frequency shift keying.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The traditional transmission of 1 Mbit in the Bluetooth Basic Rate was renamed 1M PHY in Bluetooth 5.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The new mode at a doubled symbol speed was introduced as the 2M PHY.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In Bluetooth Low Energy every transmission starts on the 1M PHY leaving it to the application to initiate a switch to the 2M PHY.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In that case both sender and receiver will switch to the 2M PHY for transmissions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This is designed to facilitate firmware updates where the application can switch back to a traditional 1M PHY in case of errors.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In reality the target device should be close to the programming station (at a few meters).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Bluetooth 5 has introduced two new modes with lower data rate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The symbol rate of the new "Coded PHY" is the same as the Base Rate 1M PHY but in mode S=2 there are two symbols transmitted per data bit.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In mode S=2 only a simple Pattern Mapping P=1 is used which simply produces the same stuffing bit for each input data bit.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In mode S=8 there are eight symbols per data bit with a Pattern Mapping P=4 producing contrasting symbol sequences – a 0 bit is encoded as binary 0011 and a 1 bit is encoded as binary 1100.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] In mode S=2 using P=1 the range doubles approximately, while in mode S=8 using P=4 it does quadruple.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The "LE Coded" transmissions have not only changed the error correction scheme but it uses a fundamentally new packet format.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Each "LE Coded" burst consists of three blocks.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The switch block ("extended preamble") is transmitted on the LE 1M PHY but it only consists of 10 times a binary '00111100' pattern.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] These 80 bits are not FEC encoded as usual but they are sent directly to the radio channel.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] It is followed by a header block ("FEC Block 1") which is always transmitted in S=8 mode.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The header block only contains the destination address ("Access Address" / 32 bit) and an encoding flag ("Coding Indicator" / 2 Bit).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The Coding Indicator defines the Pattern Mapping used for the following payload block ("FEC Block 2") where S=2 is possible.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The new packet format of Bluetooth 5 allows transmitting from 2 up to 256 bytes as the payload in a single burst.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] This is a lot more than the maximum of 31 bytes in Bluetooth 4.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] Along with reach measurements this should allow for localisation functions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] As a whole the quadrupled range—at the same transmission power—is achieved at the expense of a lower data being at an eighth with 125 kbit.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The old transmission packet format, as it continues to be used in the 1M PHY and 2M PHY modes, has been named "Uncoded" in Bluetooth 5.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-low-energy] The intermediate "LE Coded" S=2 mode allows for a 500 kbit data rate in the payload which is both beneficial for shorter latencies as well lower power consumption as the burst time itself is shorter.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth is managed by the Bluetooth Special Interest Group (SIG), which has more than 35,000 member companies in the areas of telecommunication, computing, networking, and consumer electronics.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The IEEE standardized Bluetooth as **IEEE 802.15.1** but no longer maintains the standard.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG oversees the development of the specification, manages the qualification program, and protects the trademarks.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A manufacturer must meet Bluetooth SIG standards to market it as a Bluetooth device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A network of patents applies to the technology, which is licensed to individual qualifying devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] As of 2021, 4.7 billion Bluetooth integrated circuit chips are shipped annually.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth was first demonstrated in space in 2024, an early test envisioned to enhance IoT capabilities.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The name "Bluetooth" was proposed in 1997 by Jim Kardach of Intel, one of the founders of the Bluetooth SIG.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The name was inspired by a conversation with Sven Mattisson who related Scandinavian history through tales from Frans G.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bengtsson's *The Long Ships*, a historical novel about Vikings and the 10th-century Danish king Harald Bluetooth.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Upon discovering a picture of the runestone of Harald Bluetooth in the book *A History of the Vikings* by Gwyn Jones, Kardach proposed Bluetooth as the codename for the short-range wireless program.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth is the Anglicised version of the Scandinavian *Blåtand*/*Blåtann* (or in Old Norse *blátǫnn*).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It was the epithet of King Harald Bluetooth, who united the disparate Danish tribes into a single kingdom; Kardach chose the name to imply that Bluetooth similarly unites communication protocols.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth logo is a bind rune merging the Younger Futhark runes (ᚼ, Hagall) and (ᛒ, Bjarkan), Harald's initials.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The development of the "short-link" radio technology, later named Bluetooth, was initiated in 1989 by Nils Rydbeck, CTO at Ericsson Mobile in Lund, Sweden.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The purpose was to develop wireless headsets, according to two inventions by Johan Ullman, SE 8902098-6, issued 12 June 1989 and SE 9202239, issued 24 July 1992 .
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Nils Rydbeck tasked Tord Wingren with specifying and Dutchman Jaap Haartsen and Sven Mattisson with developing.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Principal design and development began in 1994 and by 1997 the team had a workable solution.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] From 1997 Örjan Johansson became the project leader and propelled the technology and standardization.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In 1997, Adalio Sanchez, then head of IBM ThinkPad product R&D, approached Nils Rydbeck about collaborating on integrating a mobile phone into a ThinkPad notebook.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The two assigned engineers from Ericsson and IBM studied the idea.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The conclusion was that power consumption on cellphone technology at that time was too high to allow viable integration into a notebook and still achieve adequate battery life.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Instead, the two companies agreed to integrate Ericsson's short-link technology on both a ThinkPad notebook and an Ericsson phone to accomplish the goal.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Since neither IBM ThinkPad notebooks nor Ericsson phones were the market share leaders in their respective markets at that time, Adalio Sanchez and Nils Rydbeck agreed to make the short-link technology an open industry standard to permit each player maximum market access.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Ericsson contributed the short-link radio technology, and IBM contributed patents around the logical layer.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Adalio Sanchez of IBM then recruited Stephen Nachtsheim of Intel to join and then Intel also recruited Toshiba and Nokia.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In May 1998, the Bluetooth SIG was launched with IBM and Ericsson as the founding signatories and a total of five members: Ericsson, Intel, Nokia, Toshiba, and IBM.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The first Bluetooth device was revealed in 1999.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It was a hands-free mobile headset that earned the "Best of show Technology Award" at COMDEX.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The first Bluetooth mobile phone was the unreleased prototype Ericsson T36, though it was the revised Ericsson model T39 that actually made it to store shelves in June 2001.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] However Ericsson released the R520m in Quarter 1 of 2001, making the R520m the first ever commercially available Bluetooth phone.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In parallel, IBM introduced the IBM ThinkPad A30 in October 2001 which was the first notebook with integrated Bluetooth.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth's early incorporation into consumer electronics products continued at Vosi Technologies in Costa Mesa, California, initially overseen by founding members Bejan Amini and Tom Davidson.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Vosi Technologies had been created by real estate developer Ivano Stegmenga, with United States Patent 608507, for communication between a cellular phone and a vehicle's audio system.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] At the time, Sony/Ericsson had only a minor market share in the cellular phone market, which was dominated in the US by Nokia and Motorola.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Due to ongoing negotiations for an intended licensing agreement with Motorola beginning in the late 1990s, Vosi could not publicly disclose the intention, integration, and initial development of other enabled devices which were to be the first "Smart Home" internet connected devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Vosi needed a means for the system to communicate without a wired connection from the vehicle to the other devices in the network.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth was chosen, since Wi-Fi was not yet readily available or supported in the public market.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Vosi had begun to develop the Vosi Cello integrated vehicular system and some other internet connected devices, one of which was intended to be a table-top device named the Vosi Symphony, networked with Bluetooth.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Through the negotiations with Motorola, Vosi introduced and disclosed its intent to integrate Bluetooth in its devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In the early 2000s a legal battle ensued between Vosi and Motorola, which indefinitely suspended release of the devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Later, Motorola implemented it in their devices, which initiated the significant propagation of Bluetooth in the public market due to its large market share at the time.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In 2012, Jaap Haartsen was nominated by the European Patent Office for the European Inventor Award.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth operates at frequencies between 2.402 and 2.480 GHz, or 2.400 and 2.4835 GHz, including guard bands 2 MHz wide at the bottom end and 3.5 MHz wide at the top.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This is in the globally unlicensed (but not unregulated) industrial, scientific and medical (ISM) 2.4 GHz short-range radio frequency band.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth uses a radio technology called frequency-hopping spread spectrum.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth divides transmitted data into packets, and transmits each packet on one of 79 designated Bluetooth channels.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It usually performs 1600 hops per second, with adaptive frequency-hopping (AFH) enabled.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth Low Energy uses 2 MHz spacing, which accommodates 40 channels.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Originally, Gaussian frequency-shift keying (GFSK) modulation was the only modulation scheme available.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Since the introduction of Bluetooth 2.0+EDR, π/4-DQPSK (differential quadrature phase-shift keying) and 8-DPSK modulation may also be used between compatible devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Devices functioning with GFSK are said to be operating in basic rate (BR) mode, where an instantaneous bit rate of 1 Mbit/s is possible.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The term *Enhanced Data Rate* (*EDR*) is used to describe π/4-DPSK (EDR2) and 8-DPSK (EDR3) schemes, transferring 2 and 3 Mbit/s respectively.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In 2019, Apple published an extension called HDR which supports data rates of 4 (HDR4) and 8 (HDR8) Mbit/s using π/4-DQPSK modulation on 4 MHz channels with forward error correction (FEC).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth is a packet-based protocol with a master/slave architecture.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] One master may communicate with up to seven slaves in a piconet.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] All devices within a given piconet use the clock provided by the master as the base for packet exchange.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The master clock ticks with a period of 312.5 μs, two clock ticks then make up a slot of 625 μs, and two slots make up a slot pair of 1250 μs.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In the simple case of single-slot packets, the master transmits in even slots and receives in odd slots.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The slave, conversely, receives in even slots and transmits in odd slots.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Packets may be 1, 3, or 5 slots long, but in all cases, the master's transmission begins in even slots and the slave's in odd slots.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The above excludes Bluetooth Low Energy, introduced in the 4.0 specification, which uses the same spectrum but somewhat differently.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A master BR/EDR Bluetooth device can communicate with a maximum of seven devices in a piconet (an ad hoc computer network using Bluetooth technology), though not all devices reach this maximum.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The devices can switch roles, by agreement, and the slave can become the master (for example, a headset initiating a connection to a phone necessarily begins as master—as an initiator of the connection—but may subsequently operate as the slave).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth Core Specification provides for the connection of two or more piconets to form a scatternet, in which certain devices simultaneously play the master/leader role in one piconet and the slave role in another.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] At any given time, data can be transferred between the master and one other device (except for the little-used broadcast mode).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The master chooses which slave device to address; typically, it switches rapidly from one device to another in a round-robin fashion.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Since it is the master that chooses which slave to address, whereas a slave is (in theory) supposed to listen in each receive slot, being a master is a lighter burden than being a slave.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Being a master of seven slaves is possible; being a slave of more than one master is possible.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The specification is vague as to required behavior in scatternets.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth is a standard wire-replacement communications protocol primarily designed for low power consumption, with a short range based on low-cost transceiver microchips in each device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Because the devices use a radio (broadcast) communications system, they do not have to be in visual line of sight of each other; however, a *quasi optical* wireless path must be viable.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Historically, the Bluetooth range was defined by the radio class, with a lower class (and higher output power) having larger range.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The actual range of a given link depends on several qualities of both communicating devices and the air and obstacles in between.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The primary attributes affecting range are the data rate, protocol (Bluetooth Classic or Bluetooth Low Energy), transmission power, and receiver sensitivity, and the relative orientations and gains of both antennas.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The effective range varies depending on propagation conditions, material coverage, production sample variations, antenna configurations and battery conditions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Most Bluetooth applications are for indoor conditions, where attenuation of walls and signal fading due to signal reflections make the range far lower than specified line-of-sight ranges of the Bluetooth products.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Most Bluetooth applications are battery-powered Class 2 devices, with little difference in range whether the other end of the link is a Class 1 or Class 2 device as the lower-powered device tends to set the range limit.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In some cases the effective range of the data link can be extended when a Class 2 device is connecting to a Class 1 transceiver with both higher sensitivity and transmission power than a typical Class 2 device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In general, however, Class 1 devices have sensitivities similar to those of Class 2 devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Connecting two Class 1 devices with both high sensitivity and high power can allow ranges far in excess of the typical 100 m, depending on the throughput required by the application.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Some such devices allow open field ranges of up to 1 km and beyond between two similar devices without exceeding legal emission limits.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] To use Bluetooth wireless technology, a device must be able to interpret certain Bluetooth profiles.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Profiles are definitions of possible applications and specify general behaviors that Bluetooth-enabled devices use to communicate with other Bluetooth devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] These profiles include settings to parameterize and to control the communication from the start.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Adherence to profiles saves the time for transmitting the parameters anew before the bi-directional link becomes effective.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] There are a wide range of Bluetooth profiles that describe many different types of applications or use cases for devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth exists in numerous products such as telephones, speakers, tablets, media players, robotics systems, laptops, and game console equipment as well as some high definition headsets, modems, hearing aids and even watches.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth is useful when transferring information between two or more devices that are near each other in low-bandwidth situations.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth is commonly used to transfer sound data with telephones (i.e., with a Bluetooth headset) or byte data with hand-held computers (transferring files).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth protocols simplify the discovery and setup of services between devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth devices can advertise all of the services they provide.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This makes using services easier, because more of the security, network address and permission configuration can be automated than with many other network types.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A personal computer that does not have embedded Bluetooth can use a Bluetooth adapter that enables the PC to communicate with Bluetooth devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] While some desktop computers and most recent laptops come with a built-in Bluetooth radio, others require an external adapter, typically in the form of a small USB "dongle".
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Unlike its predecessor, IrDA, which requires a separate adapter for each device, Bluetooth lets multiple devices communicate with a computer over a single adapter.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] For Microsoft platforms, Windows XP Service Pack 2 and SP3 releases work natively with Bluetooth v1.1, v2.0 and v2.0+EDR.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Previous versions required users to install their Bluetooth adapter's own drivers, which were not directly supported by Microsoft.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Microsoft's own Bluetooth dongles (packaged with their Bluetooth computer devices) have no external drivers and thus require at least Windows XP Service Pack 2.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Windows Vista RTM/SP1 with the Feature Pack for Wireless or Windows Vista SP2 work with Bluetooth v2.1+EDR.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Windows 7 works with Bluetooth v2.1+EDR and Extended Inquiry Response (EIR).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Windows XP and Windows Vista/Windows 7 Bluetooth stacks support the following Bluetooth profiles natively: PAN, SPP, DUN, HID, HCRP.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Windows XP stack can be replaced by a third party stack that supports more profiles or newer Bluetooth versions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Windows Vista/Windows 7 Bluetooth stack supports vendor-supplied additional profiles without requiring that the Microsoft stack be replaced.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Windows 8 and later support Bluetooth Low Energy (BLE).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It is generally recommended to install the latest vendor driver and its associated stack to be able to use the Bluetooth device at its fullest extent.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Apple products have worked with Bluetooth since Mac OS X v10.2, which was released in 2002.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Linux has two popular Bluetooth stacks, BlueZ and Fluoride.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The BlueZ stack is included with most Linux kernels and was originally developed by Qualcomm.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Fluoride, earlier known as Bluedroid, is included in Android OS and was originally developed by Broadcom.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] There is also Affix stack, developed by Nokia.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It was once popular, but has not been updated since 2005.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] FreeBSD has included Bluetooth since its v5.0 release, implemented through netgraph.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] NetBSD has included Bluetooth since its v4.0 release.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Its Bluetooth stack was ported to OpenBSD as well, however OpenBSD later removed it as unmaintained.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] DragonFly BSD has had NetBSD's Bluetooth implementation since 1.11 (2008).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A netgraph-based implementation from FreeBSD has also been available in the tree, possibly disabled until 2014-11-15, and may require more work.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The specifications were formalized by the Bluetooth Special Interest Group (SIG) and formally announced on 20 May 1998.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In 2014 it had a membership of over 30,000 companies worldwide.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It was established by Ericsson, IBM, Intel, Nokia and Toshiba, and later joined by many other companies.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] All versions of the Bluetooth standards are backward-compatible with all earlier versions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This version of the Bluetooth Core Specification was released before 2005.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The main difference is the introduction of an Enhanced Data Rate (EDR) for faster data transfer.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The data rate of EDR is 3 Mbit/s, although the maximum data transfer rate (allowing for inter-packet time and acknowledgements) is 2.1 Mbit/s.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] EDR uses a combination of GFSK and phase-shift keying modulation (PSK) with two variants, π/4-DQPSK and 8-DPSK.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] EDR can provide a lower power consumption through a reduced duty cycle.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The specification is published as *Bluetooth v2.0 + EDR*, which implies that EDR is an optional feature.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Aside from EDR, the v2.0 specification contains other minor improvements, and products may claim compliance to "Bluetooth v2.0" without supporting the higher data rate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] At least one commercial device states "Bluetooth v2.0 without EDR" on its data sheet.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth Core Specification version 2.1 + EDR was adopted by the Bluetooth SIG on 26 July 2007.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The headline feature of v2.1 is secure simple pairing (SSP): this improves the pairing experience for Bluetooth devices, while increasing the use and strength of security.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Version 2.1 allows various other improvements, including *extended inquiry response* (EIR), which provides more information during the inquiry procedure to allow better filtering of devices before connection; and sniff subrating, which reduces the power consumption in low-power mode.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Version 3.0 + HS of the Bluetooth Core Specification was adopted by the Bluetooth SIG on 21 April 2009.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth v3.0 + HS provides theoretical data transfer speeds of up to 24 Mbit/s, though not over the Bluetooth link itself.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Instead, the Bluetooth link is used for negotiation and establishment, and the high data rate traffic is carried over a colocated 802.11 link.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The main new feature is AMP (Alternative MAC/PHY), the addition of 802.11 as a high-speed transport.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The high-speed part of the specification is not mandatory, and hence only devices that display the "+HS" logo actually support Bluetooth over 802.11 high-speed data transfer.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A Bluetooth v3.0 device without the "+HS" suffix is only required to support features introduced in Core Specification version 3.0 or earlier Core Specification Addendum 1.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Enhanced Retransmission Mode (ERTM) implements reliable L2CAP channel, while Streaming Mode (SM) implements unreliable channel with no retransmission or flow control.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Introduced in Core Specification Addendum 1.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] for transporting Bluetooth profile data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth radio is still used for device discovery, initial connection and profile configuration.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] However, when large quantities of data must be sent, the high-speed alternative MAC PHY 802.11 (typically associated with Wi-Fi) transports the data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This means that Bluetooth uses proven low power connection models when the system is idle, and the faster radio when it must send large quantities of data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Permits sending service data without establishing an explicit L2CAP channel.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It is intended for use by applications that require low latency between user action and reconnection/transmission of data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This is only appropriate for small amounts of data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Updates the power control feature to remove the open loop power control, and also to clarify ambiguities in power control introduced by the new modulation schemes added for EDR.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Enhanced power control removes the ambiguities by specifying the behavior that is expected.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The feature also adds closed loop power control, meaning RSSI filtering can start as the response is received.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Additionally, a "go straight to maximum power" request has been introduced.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This is expected to deal with the headset link loss issue typically observed when a user puts their phone into a pocket on the opposite side to the headset.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The high-speed (AMP) feature of Bluetooth v3.0 was originally intended for UWB, but the WiMedia Alliance, the body responsible for the flavor of UWB intended for Bluetooth, announced in March 2009 that it was disbanding, and ultimately UWB was omitted from the Core v3.0 specification.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] On 16 March 2009, the WiMedia Alliance announced it was entering into technology transfer agreements for the WiMedia Ultra-wideband (UWB) specifications.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] WiMedia has transferred all current and future specifications, including work on future high-speed and power-optimized implementations, to the Bluetooth Special Interest Group (SIG), Wireless USB Promoter Group and the USB Implementers Forum.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] After successful completion of the technology transfer, marketing, and related administrative items, the WiMedia Alliance ceased operations.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In October 2009, the Bluetooth Special Interest Group suspended development of UWB as part of the alternative MAC/PHY, Bluetooth v3.0 + HS solution.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] A small, but significant, number of former WiMedia members had not and would not sign up to the necessary agreements for the IP transfer.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] As of 2009, the Bluetooth SIG was in the process of evaluating other options for its longer-term roadmap.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG completed the Bluetooth Core Specification version 4.0 (called Bluetooth Smart) and has been adopted as of 30 June 2010.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] It includes *Classic Bluetooth*, *Bluetooth high speed* and *Bluetooth Low Energy* (BLE) protocols.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth high speed is based on Wi-Fi, and Classic Bluetooth consists of legacy Bluetooth protocols.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth Low Energy, previously known as Wibree, is a subset of Bluetooth v4.0 with an entirely new protocol stack for rapid build-up of simple links.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] As an alternative to the Bluetooth standard protocols that were introduced in Bluetooth v1.0 to v3.0, it is aimed at very low power applications powered by a coin cell.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Chip designs allow for two types of implementation, dual-mode, single-mode and enhanced past versions.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The provisional names *Wibree* and *Bluetooth ULP* (Ultra Low Power) were abandoned and the BLE name was used for a while.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In late 2011, new logos "Bluetooth Smart Ready" for hosts and "Bluetooth Smart" for sensors were introduced as the general-public face of BLE.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Compared to *Classic Bluetooth*, Bluetooth Low Energy is intended to provide considerably reduced power consumption and cost while maintaining a similar communication range.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In terms of lengthening the battery life of Bluetooth devices, BLE represents a significant progression.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] General improvements in version 4.0 include the changes necessary to facilitate BLE modes, as well the Generic Attribute Profile (GATT) and Security Manager (SM) services with AES Encryption.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Core Specification Addendum 2 was unveiled in December 2011; it contains improvements to the audio Host Controller Interface and to the High Speed (802.11) Protocol Adaptation Layer.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Core Specification Addendum 3 revision 2 has an adoption date of 24 July 2012.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Core Specification Addendum 4 has an adoption date of 12 February 2013.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG announced formal adoption of the Bluetooth v4.1 specification on 4 December 2013.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] This specification is an incremental software update to Bluetooth Specification v4.0, and not a hardware update.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The update incorporates Bluetooth Core Specification Addenda (CSA 1, 2, 3 & 4) and adds new features that improve consumer usability.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] These include increased co-existence support for LTE, bulk data exchange rates—and aid developer innovation by allowing devices to support multiple roles simultaneously.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Some features were already available in a Core Specification Addendum (CSA) before the release of v4.1.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Released on 2 December 2014, it introduces features for the Internet of things.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Older Bluetooth hardware may receive 4.2 features such as Data Packet Length Extension and improved privacy via firmware updates.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG released Bluetooth 5 on 6 December 2016.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Its new features are mainly focused on new Internet of Things technology.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Sony was the first to announce Bluetooth 5.0 support with its Xperia XZ Premium in Feb 2017 during the Mobile World Congress 2017.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Samsung Galaxy S8 launched with Bluetooth 5 support in April 2017.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] In September 2017, the iPhone 8, 8 Plus and iPhone X launched with Bluetooth 5 support as well.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Apple also integrated Bluetooth 5 in its new HomePod offering released on 9 February 2018.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth 5 provides, for BLE, options that can double the data rate (2 Mbit/s burst) at the expense of range, or provide up to four times the range at the expense of data rate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The increase in transmissions could be important for Internet of Things devices, where many nodes connect throughout a whole house.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] Bluetooth 5 increases capacity of connectionless services such as location-relevant navigation of low-energy Bluetooth connections.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG presented Bluetooth 5.1 on 21 January 2019.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] On 31 December 2019, the Bluetooth SIG published the Bluetooth Core Specification version 5.2.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG published the Bluetooth Core Specification version 5.3 on 13 July 2021.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG released the Bluetooth Core Specification version 5.4 on 7 February 2023.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG released the Bluetooth Core Specification version 6.0 on 27 August 2024.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG released the Bluetooth Core Specification version 6.1 on 7 May 2025.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p01] The Bluetooth SIG released the Bluetooth Core Specification version 6.2 on 3 November 2025.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Seeking to extend the compatibility of Bluetooth devices, the devices that adhere to the standard use an interface called HCI (Host Controller Interface) between the host and the controller.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The L2CAP protocol is responsible for the segmentation and reassembly of the packets.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The hardware that makes up the Bluetooth device is made up of, logically, two parts; which may or may not be physically separate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] A radio device, responsible for modulating and transmitting the signal; and a digital controller.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The digital controller is likely a CPU, one of whose functions is to run a Link Controller; and interfaces with the host device; but some functions may be delegated to hardware.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Link Controller is responsible for the processing of the baseband and the management of ARQ and physical layer FEC protocols.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In addition, it handles the transfer functions (both asynchronous and synchronous), audio coding (e.g.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The CPU of the device is responsible for attending the instructions related to Bluetooth of the host device, in order to simplify its operation.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] To do this, the CPU runs software called Link Manager that has the function of communicating with other devices through the LMP protocol.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] A Bluetooth device is a short-range wireless device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth devices are fabricated on RF CMOS integrated circuit (RF circuit) chips.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth is defined as a layer protocol architecture consisting of core protocols, cable replacement protocols, telephony control protocols, and adopted protocols.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Mandatory protocols for all Bluetooth stacks are LMP, L2CAP and SDP.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In addition, devices that communicate with Bluetooth almost universally can use these protocols: HCI and RFCOMM.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Link Manager (LM) is the system that manages establishing the connection between devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] It is responsible for the establishment, authentication and configuration of the link.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Link Manager locates other managers and communicates with them via the management protocol of the LMP link.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] To perform its function as a service provider, the LM uses the services included in the Link Controller (LC).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Link Manager Protocol basically consists of several PDUs (Protocol Data Units) that are sent from one device to another.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Host Controller Interface provides a command interface between the controller and the host.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The *Logical Link Control and Adaptation Protocol* (L2CAP) is used to multiplex multiple logical connections between two devices using different higher level protocols.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Provides segmentation and reassembly of on-air packets.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In *Basic* mode, L2CAP provides packets with a payload configurable up to 64 kB, with 672 bytes as the default MTU, and 48 bytes as the minimum mandatory supported MTU.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In *Retransmission and Flow Control* modes, L2CAP can be configured either for isochronous data or reliable data per channel by performing retransmissions and CRC checks.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth Core Specification Addendum 1 adds two additional L2CAP modes to the core specification.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This mode is an improved version of the original retransmission mode.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This mode provides a reliable L2CAP channel.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This is a very simple mode, with no retransmission or flow control.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This mode provides an unreliable L2CAP channel.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Reliability in any of these modes is optionally and/or additionally guaranteed by the lower layer Bluetooth BDR/EDR air interface by configuring the number of retransmissions and flush timeout (time after which the radio flushes packets).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In-order sequencing is guaranteed by the lower layer.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Only L2CAP channels configured in ERTM or SM may be operated over AMP logical links.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The *Service Discovery Protocol* (SDP) allows a device to discover services offered by other devices, and their associated parameters.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Each service is identified by a Universally unique identifier (UUID), with official services (Bluetooth profiles) assigned a short form UUID (16 bits rather than the full 128).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] RFCOMM provides a simple, reliable, data stream to the user, similar to TCP.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] It is used directly by many telephony related profiles as a carrier for AT commands, as well as being a transport layer for OBEX over Bluetooth.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Many Bluetooth applications use RFCOMM because of its widespread support and publicly available API on most operating systems.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Additionally, applications that used a serial port to communicate can be quickly ported to use RFCOMM.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The *Bluetooth Network Encapsulation Protocol* (BNEP) is used for transferring another protocol stack's data via an L2CAP channel.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Its main purpose is the transmission of IP packets in the Personal Area Networking Profile.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] BNEP performs a similar function to SNAP in Wireless LAN.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The *Audio/Video Control Transport Protocol* (AVCTP) is used by the remote control profile to transfer AV/C commands over an L2CAP channel.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The music control buttons on a stereo headset use this protocol to control the music player.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The *Audio/Video Distribution Transport Protocol* (AVDTP) is used by the advanced audio distribution (A2DP) profile to stream music to stereo headsets over an L2CAP channel intended for video distribution profile in the Bluetooth transmission.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The *Telephony Control Protocol – Binary* (TCS BIN) is the bit-oriented protocol that defines the call control signaling for the establishment of voice and data calls between Bluetooth devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] TCS-BIN is only used by the cordless telephony profile, which failed to attract implementers.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] As such it is only of historical interest.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Adopted protocols are defined by other standards-making organizations and incorporated into Bluetooth's protocol stack, allowing Bluetooth to code protocols only when necessary.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] WAE specifies an application framework for wireless devices and WAP is an open standard to provide mobile users access to telephony and information services.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Depending on packet type, individual packets may be protected by error correction, either 1/3 rate forward error correction (FEC) or 2/3 rate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In addition, packets with CRC will be retransmitted until acknowledged by automatic repeat request (ARQ).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Any device may perform an inquiry to find other devices to connect to, and any device can be configured to respond to such inquiries.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] However, if the device trying to connect knows the address of the device, it always responds to direct connection requests and transmits the information shown in the list above if requested.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Use of a device's services may require pairing or acceptance by its owner, but the connection itself can be initiated by any device and held until it goes out of range.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Some devices can be connected to only one device at a time, and connecting to them prevents them from connecting to other devices and appearing in inquiries until they disconnect from the other device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Every device has a unique 48-bit address.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] However, these addresses are generally not shown in inquiries.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Instead, friendly Bluetooth names are used, which can be set by the user.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This name appears when another user scans for devices and in lists of paired devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Most cellular phones have the Bluetooth name set to the manufacturer and model of the phone by default.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Most cellular phones and laptops show only the Bluetooth names and special programs are required to get additional information about remote devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This can be confusing as, for example, there could be several cellular phones in range named T610 (see Bluejacking).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Many services offered over Bluetooth can expose private data or let a connecting party control the Bluetooth device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Security reasons make it necessary to recognize specific devices, and thus enable control over which devices can connect to a given Bluetooth device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] At the same time, it is useful for Bluetooth devices to be able to establish a connection without user intervention (for example, as soon as in range).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] To resolve this conflict, Bluetooth uses a process called *bonding*, and a bond is generated through a process called *pairing*.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] These two cases are referred to as dedicated bonding and general bonding respectively.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Pairing often involves some level of user interaction.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This user interaction confirms the identity of the devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] When pairing completes, a bond forms between the two devices, enabling those two devices to connect in the future without repeating the pairing process to confirm device identities.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] When desired, the user can remove the bonding relationship.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] During pairing, the two devices establish a relationship by creating a shared secret known as a *link key*.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] If both devices store the same link key, they are said to be *paired* or *bonded*.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] A device that wants to communicate only with a bonded device can cryptographically authenticate the identity of the other device, ensuring it is the same device it previously paired with.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Once a link key is generated, an authenticated ACL link between the devices may be encrypted to protect exchanged data against eavesdropping.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Users can delete link keys from either device, which removes the bond between the devices—so it is possible for one device to have a stored link key for a device it is no longer paired with.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth services generally require either encryption or authentication and as such require pairing before they let a remote device connect.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Some services, such as the Object Push Profile, elect not to explicitly require authentication or encryption so that pairing does not interfere with the user experience associated with the service use-cases.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Pairing mechanisms changed significantly with the introduction of Secure Simple Pairing in Bluetooth v2.1.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Prior to Bluetooth v2.1, encryption is not required and can be turned off at any time.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Moreover, the encryption key is only good for approximately 23.5 hours; using a single encryption key longer than this time allows simple XOR attacks to retrieve the encryption key.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Link keys may be stored on the device file system, not on the Bluetooth chip itself.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Many Bluetooth chip manufacturers let link keys be stored on the device—however, if the device is removable, this means that the link key moves with the device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth implements confidentiality, authentication and key derivation with custom algorithms based on the SAFER+ block cipher.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth key generation is generally based on a Bluetooth PIN, which must be entered into both devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This procedure might be modified if one of the devices has a fixed PIN (e.g., for headsets or similar devices with a restricted user interface).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] During pairing, an initialization key or master key is generated, using the E22 algorithm.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The E0 stream cipher is used for encrypting packets, granting confidentiality, and is based on a shared cryptographic secret, namely a previously generated link key or master key.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Those keys, used for subsequent encryption of data sent via the air interface, rely on the Bluetooth PIN, which has been entered into one or both devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] An overview of Bluetooth vulnerabilities exploits was published in 2007 by Andreas Becker.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In September 2008, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) published a Guide to Bluetooth Security as a reference for organizations.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] It describes Bluetooth security capabilities and how to secure Bluetooth technologies effectively.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] While Bluetooth has its benefits, it is susceptible to denial-of-service attacks, eavesdropping, man-in-the-middle attacks, message modification, and resource misappropriation.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Users and organizations must evaluate their acceptable level of risk and incorporate security into the lifecycle of Bluetooth devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] To help mitigate risks, included in the NIST document are security checklists with guidelines and recommendations for creating and maintaining secure Bluetooth piconets, headsets, and smart card readers.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth v2.1 – finalized in 2007 with consumer devices first appearing in 2009 – makes significant changes to Bluetooth's security, including pairing.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] See the pairing mechanisms section for more about these changes.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluejacking is the sending of either a picture or a message from one user to an unsuspecting user through Bluetooth wireless technology.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Common applications include short messages, e.g., "You've just been bluejacked!" Bluejacking does not involve the removal or alteration of any data from the device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In 2001, Jakobsson and Wetzel from Bell Laboratories discovered flaws in the Bluetooth pairing protocol and also pointed to vulnerabilities in the encryption scheme.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Digital Ltd. discovered that serious flaws in some poor implementations of Bluetooth security may lead to disclosure of personal data.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In a subsequent experiment, Martin Herfurt from the trifinite.group was able to do a field-trial at the CeBIT fairgrounds, showing the importance of the problem to the world.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] A new attack called BlueBug was used for this experiment.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In 2004 the first purported virus using Bluetooth to spread itself among mobile phones appeared on the Symbian OS.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The virus was first described by Kaspersky Lab and requires users to confirm the installation of unknown software before it can propagate.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The virus was written as a proof-of-concept by a group of virus writers known as "29A" and sent to anti-virus groups.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Thus, it should be regarded as a potential (but not real) security threat to Bluetooth technology or Symbian OS since the virus has never spread outside of this system.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In August 2004, a world-record-setting experiment (see also Bluetooth sniping) showed that the range of Class 2 Bluetooth radios could be extended to 1.78 km (1.11 mi) with directional antennas and signal amplifiers.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This poses a potential security threat because it enables attackers to access vulnerable Bluetooth devices from a distance beyond expectation.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The attacker must also be able to receive information from the victim to set up a connection.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] No attack can be made against a Bluetooth device unless the attacker knows its Bluetooth address and which channels to transmit on, although these can be deduced within a few minutes if the device is in use.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In January 2005, a mobile malware worm known as Lasco surfaced.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The worm began targeting mobile phones using Symbian OS (Series 60 platform) using Bluetooth enabled devices to replicate itself and spread to other devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The worm is self-installing and begins once the mobile user approves the transfer of the file (Velasco.sis) from another device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Once installed, the worm begins looking for other Bluetooth enabled devices to infect.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Additionally, the worm infects other .SIS files on the device, allowing replication to another device through the use of removable media (Secure Digital, CompactFlash, etc.).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The worm can render the mobile device unstable.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In April 2005, University of Cambridge security researchers published results of their actual implementation of passive attacks against the PIN-based pairing between commercial Bluetooth devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] They confirmed that attacks are practicably fast, and the Bluetooth symmetric key establishment method is vulnerable.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] To rectify this vulnerability, they designed an implementation that showed that stronger, asymmetric key establishment is feasible for certain classes of devices, such as mobile phones.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In June 2005, Yaniv Shaked and Avishai Wool published a paper describing both passive and active methods for obtaining the PIN for a Bluetooth link.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The passive attack allows a suitably equipped attacker to eavesdrop on communications and spoof if the attacker was present at the time of initial pairing.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The active method makes use of a specially constructed message that must be inserted at a specific point in the protocol, to make the master and slave repeat the pairing process.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] After that, the first method can be used to crack the PIN.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] This attack's major weakness is that it requires the user of the devices under attack to re-enter the PIN during the attack when the device prompts them to.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Also, this active attack probably requires custom hardware, since most commercially available Bluetooth devices are not capable of the timing necessary.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In August 2005, police in Cambridgeshire, England, issued warnings about thieves using Bluetooth enabled phones to track other devices left in cars.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Police are advising users to ensure that any mobile networking connections are de-activated if laptops and other devices are left in this way.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In April 2006, researchers from Secure Network and F-Secure published a report that warns of the large number of devices left in a visible state, and issued statistics on the spread of various Bluetooth services and the ease of spread of an eventual Bluetooth worm.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In October 2006, at the Luxembourgish Hack.lu Security Conference, Kevin Finistere and Thierry Zoller demonstrated and released a remote root shell via Bluetooth on Mac OS X v10.3.9 and v10.4.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] They also demonstrated the first Bluetooth PIN and Linkkeys cracker, which is based on the research of Wool and Shaked.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In April 2017, security researchers at Armis discovered multiple exploits in the Bluetooth software in various platforms, including Microsoft Windows, Linux, Apple iOS, and Google Android.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] These vulnerabilities are collectively called "BlueBorne".
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The exploits allow an attacker to connect to devices or systems without authentication and can give them "virtually full control over the device".
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Armis contacted Google, Microsoft, Apple, Samsung and Linux developers allowing them to patch their software before the coordinated announcement of the vulnerabilities on 12 September 2017.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In July 2018, Lior Neumann and Eli Biham, researchers at the Technion – Israel Institute of Technology identified a security vulnerability in the latest Bluetooth pairing procedures: Secure Simple Pairing and LE Secure Connections.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The researcher demonstrated the attack on various devices of different categories and from different manufacturers.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Google released an Android security patch on 5 August 2019, which removed this vulnerability.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] In November 2023, researchers from Eurecom revealed a new class of attacks known as BLUFFS (Bluetooth Low Energy Forward and Future Secrecy Attacks).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] These 6 new attacks expand on and work in conjunction with the previously known KNOB and BIAS (Bluetooth Impersonation AttackS) attacks.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] While the previous KNOB and BIAS attacks allowed an attacker to decrypt and spoof Bluetooth packets within a session, BLUFFS extends this capability to all sessions generated by a device (including past, present, and future).
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] All devices running Bluetooth versions 4.2 up to and including 5.4 are affected.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth uses the radio frequency spectrum in the 2.402 GHz to 2.480 GHz range, which is non-ionizing radiation, of similar bandwidth to that used by wireless and mobile phones.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] No specific harm has been demonstrated, even though wireless transmission has been included by IARC in the possible carcinogen list.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Maximum power output from a Bluetooth radio is 100 mW for Class 1, 2.5 mW for Class 2, and 1 mW for Class 3 devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Even the maximum power output of Class 1 is a lower level than the lowest-powered mobile phones.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Bluetooth Innovation World Cup, a marketing initiative of the Bluetooth Special Interest Group (SIG), was an international competition that encouraged the development of innovations for applications leveraging Bluetooth technology in sports, fitness and health care products.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The competition aimed to stimulate new markets.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Bluetooth Innovation World Cup morphed into the Bluetooth Breakthrough Awards in 2013.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] Bluetooth SIG subsequently launched the Imagine Blue Award in 2016 at Bluetooth World.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetooth-p02] The Bluetooth Breakthrough Awards program highlights the most innovative products and applications available today, prototypes coming soon, and student-led projects in the making.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] The BluetoothDevice interface of the Web Bluetooth API represents a Bluetooth device inside a particular script execution environment.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] A string that uniquely identifies a device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] A string that provides a human-readable name for the device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] A reference to the device's `BluetoothRemoteGATTServer`.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] A `Promise` that resolves to `undefined` or is rejected with an error if advertisements can't be shown for any reason.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] Provides a way for the page to revoke access to a device the user has granted access to.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] Listen to these events using `addEventListener()` or by assigning an event listener to the `oneventname` property of this interface.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothdevice] Fired on a device when an active GATT connection is lost.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] The **`BluetoothRemoteGATTServer`** interface of the Web Bluetooth API represents a GATT Server on a remote device.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] A boolean value that returns true while this script execution environment is connected to `this.device`.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] It can be false while the user agent is physically connected.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] A reference to the `BluetoothDevice` running the server.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] Causes the script execution environment to connect to `this.device`.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] Causes the script execution environment to disconnect from `this.device`.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] Returns a promise to the primary `BluetoothRemoteGATTService` offered by the Bluetooth device for a specified `BluetoothServiceUUID`.
[src:web-bluetooth/bluetoothremotegattserver] Returns a promise to a list of primary `BluetoothRemoteGATTService` objects offered by the Bluetooth device for a specified `BluetoothServiceUUID`.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] The Web Bluetooth API provides the ability to connect and interact with Bluetooth Low Energy peripherals.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Provides methods to query Bluetooth availability and request access to devices.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Provides properties of a particular `BluetoothRemoteGATTCharacteristic`.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Represents a Bluetooth device inside a particular script execution environment.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Represents a GATT Characteristic, which is a basic data element that provides further information about a peripheral's service.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Represents a GATT Descriptor, which provides further information about a characteristic's value.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Represents a GATT Server on a remote device.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Represents a service provided by a GATT server, including a device, a list of referenced services, and a list of the characteristics of this service.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] The Bluetooth API extends the following APIs, adding the listed features.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Returns a `Bluetooth` object for the current document, providing access to Web Bluetooth API functionality.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] The Web Bluetooth API can only be used in a secure context.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Access to the API is controlled by the Permissions Policy directive `bluetooth`.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] The default allowlist for the `bluetooth` policy is `self`, which enables Bluetooth usage in same-origin nested frames but prevents access by third-party content by default.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] Cross-origin access is enabled by specifying the allowed origins in both the `Permissions-Policy: bluetooth` HTTP header and the desired `<iframe>`.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] In order to use the feature the user must first grant explicit permission (they will not be prompted for access if it is not allowed for other reasons, such as being blocked by a Permissions Policy).
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] The permission prompt is displayed when calling `Bluetooth.requestDevice()` to request access to a new Bluetooth device for which permission is not granted (the owning global object must also have transient activation).
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] You can use `Bluetooth.getDevices()` to retrieve any devices that have previously been granted permission for the site.
[src:web-bluetooth/web-bluetooth-api] The Permissions API `navigator.permissions.query()` method can be used with the `bluetooth` permission to test whether a site has permission to use Bluetooth devices.
